# Authentication & Security

## JWT Architecture

- Auth service issues JWT tokens via `POST /api/v1/login`.
- All other services validate tokens using shared `Jwt:Key`, `Jwt:Issuer`, `Jwt:Audience` config.
- Tokens use `HmacSha256` symmetric signing.
- Token lifetime is configured per service; inter-service tokens use 6-hour expiry.

## Claim-Based Authorization

Claims defined in `ClaimIds`:
- `username` — user identity
- `admin` — system-wide admin
- `mealsAdmin` — admin access to Meals domain
- `mealsUser` — standard user access to Meals domain
- `mealsService` — inter-service claim for Meals calling Kitchen
- `patientsService` — inter-service claim for Patient calling Meals

### Policy Mapping

| Service | Policy | Required Claim |
|---------|--------|---------------|
| Patient | `Admin` | `admin` |
| Patient | `PatientAdmin` | `admin` (patient-level) |
| Patient | `PatientAdminOrMealsService` | `admin` OR `mealsService` |
| Meals | `MealsAdmin` | `mealsAdmin` |
| Meals | `MealsUser` | `mealsUser` |
| Meals | `PatientService` | `patientsService` |
| Kitchen | `MealsService` | `mealsService` |
| Kitchen | `KitchenUser` | `kitchenUser` |

## Inter-Service Auth

- Meals service uses `MealsServiceTokenHandler` (a `DelegatingHandler`) that auto-generates a JWT with the appropriate service claim before making HTTP calls to Patient or Kitchen APIs.
- Never hard-code tokens. Always generate via the token handler.

## Frontend Auth

- Store JWT in memory or secure storage (not localStorage for sensitive tokens)
- Attach token via an `HttpInterceptor` on all API requests
- Implement an `AuthGuard` to protect domain routes
- Redirect to `/login` on 401 responses
- Do NOT store secrets or JWT keys in the frontend
